    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi> | (<hi rend="print">Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi>)</placeName>
                    <date>Jan. 28<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1881</date>
                    <salute>My dear Balfour</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
                    <p>I must write a few lines to thank you cordially for all that you have done about the letter in Nature.— The translation is as clear as daylight. For the future I shall not care if M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Butler calls me a liar, thief or murderer.<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
<p>Again thanking you, believe me, Yours very sincerely | Charles Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">0.1 (<hi rend="italic">Railway … S.E.R.</hi>)] <hi rend="italic">parentheses added</hi> </note>
            </div>
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Balfour had translated <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2758.xml">Ernst Krause</ref>’s response to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_774.xml">Samuel Butler</ref>; it was published as a letter in <hi rend="italic">Nature</hi>, 27 January 1881, p. 288 (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-13007.xml">letter to F. M. Balfour, 12 January 1881</ref>).</note>    
        </div>
    
